WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:29.140
and welcome to Veterans of the Valley.

00:29.140 --> 00:33.780
Tom Tom Turboville. It's a simple fact that World War II could not have been

00:33.780 --> 00:38.460
thought much less one without naval construction battalions better known as

00:38.460 --> 00:42.860
C-Bees. Today you'll meet John Blazons of Bryan but I dare say that many of you

00:42.860 --> 00:47.860
already know him. After all he has lived all but ten of his 82 years in Bryan.

00:47.860 --> 00:52.700
Born in Bryan, proud member of Stephen F Austin High School class of 1942.

00:52.700 --> 00:58.660
Aggie class of 1947 and a proud sailor with the 105th C-Bees serving the

00:58.660 --> 01:02.300
Pacific campaign at Australia, New Guinea and the Philippines at the late

01:02.300 --> 01:05.980
take off. It's a pleasure to have you on Veterans of the Valley. I want to talk

01:05.980 --> 01:10.460
about a man who probably knows Bryan as well as anybody. You were born here. I

01:10.460 --> 01:14.260
know your dad was in the grocery business and also in the cotton business here.

01:14.260 --> 01:18.500
Born in Bryan and spent like we said all but ten years in Bryan. Talk about

01:18.500 --> 01:22.900
what Bryan, Texas, was like back in the the 1930s I guess when you were just a

01:22.900 --> 01:28.380
young kid growing up. What was the town like? Well Bryan was Main Street. A few

01:28.380 --> 01:35.940
businesses on Bryan Street. Basically everything went up and down Main Street.

01:35.940 --> 01:42.420
All the grocery stores were there as well. There's the clothing stores and

01:42.420 --> 01:48.980
the drug stores just about anything that you wanted at that time. So what we know

01:48.980 --> 01:52.780
is downtown Bryan now that's just where practically all the commerce was. When

01:52.780 --> 01:55.820
you wanted to buy something go to the grocery store, go to a movie, go get

01:55.820 --> 02:00.220
clothes, you went to downtown Bryan. That's true. You parked at the curb and walked

02:00.220 --> 02:04.760
into the bin as you wanted to deal with and then you drove two blocks down the

02:04.760 --> 02:08.780
street and parked at the curb again. Right. Right. And Bryan as we know it today

02:08.780 --> 02:12.660
wasn't anything like it then. It was pretty much a shrunk version of what we

02:12.660 --> 02:18.300
see now because the paved roads were sort of few and far between. Right? That's

02:18.300 --> 02:24.700
correct. Texas Avenue was Highway 6 and there was a paved street that went west to

02:24.700 --> 02:29.100
serve Boo Elementary School and there was a paved street that went east to serve

02:29.100 --> 02:33.300
Travis Elementary School. Right. That was pretty near it. So if you wanted to get

02:33.300 --> 02:37.940
from Bryan say a downtown Bryan to Texas A&M you would take Highway 6 up to

02:37.940 --> 02:41.540
what we know is the as the bins right now and then that would go on to

02:41.540 --> 02:45.100
College Avenue on to campus. That's how you got to campus right? College Avenue

02:45.100 --> 02:51.300
Old College Road and what is now a well-run road to get to campus. Right. Of course

02:51.300 --> 02:55.420
you had Texas A&M on the on the other side and then you had Bryan. What was

02:55.420 --> 03:01.500
how did the how did the citizenry and all of that deal with Texas A&M?

03:01.500 --> 03:07.020
Obviously Texas A&M was a big industry there just like it is now. Yes and of

03:07.020 --> 03:12.780
course Bryan probably felt then much like College Station does now. The home of

03:12.780 --> 03:18.060
Texas A&M. Right. Right. Right. It was the agriculture and mechanical college. You

03:18.060 --> 03:21.740
said that your dad was in the cotton business. Cotton was a big industry back

03:21.740 --> 03:26.260
then in in Bryan and that had a lot to do with the railroad I guess right? Well

03:26.260 --> 03:34.980
cotton was the valley the branches bottom the farmers raised mostly cotton as

03:34.980 --> 03:41.460
far as a pay. Right. Right. Right. You went to Stephen F. Austin as a matter of

03:41.460 --> 03:46.300
fact this this past summer it's actually after we're taping this but before

03:46.300 --> 03:51.820
it's airing on TV in June you had a reunion at the class of 1942 of Stephen

03:51.820 --> 03:55.300
F. Austin high school. A lot of people of course obviously know that was the

03:55.300 --> 04:00.140
pre of what we know now is Bryan high school. Talk a little bit about Stephen

04:00.140 --> 04:04.700
F. Austin back in the back in the 40s obviously it was a it was a wonderful

04:04.700 --> 04:09.300
school a lot of great memories. Well yes Stephen F. Austin was a new high school

04:09.300 --> 04:16.620
and the more junior high school originated in the original high school

04:16.620 --> 04:21.600
building so that when I went Stephen F. Austin was only about three three

