of football support of course that was still the number one sport. Speaking of

04:33.740 --> 04:38.100
football you were the class of 1942 but you actually didn't receive your

04:38.100 --> 04:41.980
diploma until after the fall of 1942 and that had something to do with

04:41.980 --> 04:45.940
football and your desire to play quarterback that last year in the fall of

04:45.940 --> 04:51.020
42 sort of talk about how that worked. Well it was just fact that you could play

04:51.020 --> 04:59.340
high school football until you were 18 and so I was 17 and was eligible to play

04:59.340 --> 05:07.820
another semester. Right. Did not graduate in May of 42 but came back that

05:07.820 --> 05:11.180
fall and took one took an English class or something like that or took a

05:11.180 --> 05:13.980
couple of classes in the fall so you could be eligible for football right.

05:13.980 --> 05:19.660
Yes English was one of the state mandated courses right if you didn't have all

05:19.660 --> 05:23.260
your English credits you couldn't graduate. Right so you waited to the fall to

05:23.260 --> 05:26.540
take that so you could play football and then and then finished and I think you

05:26.540 --> 05:30.020
told me you were the first T-formation quarterback of Brian of Brian

05:30.020 --> 05:35.860
higher Stephen F. Austin right. Yes that's true. That's great. Right after you

05:35.860 --> 05:39.540
graduated from from high school you you entered Texas A&M so actually that

05:39.540 --> 05:43.780
would have been in the in the spring semester I guess earlier January of

05:43.780 --> 05:48.540
of 1943 that's when you enter Texas A&M. That's correct yeah yeah. I went one

05:48.540 --> 05:52.620
semester to Texas A&M and then the course we were already involved in the

05:52.620 --> 05:57.060
war this being in 1943 then talk about your desire to enter the service and

05:57.060 --> 06:01.580
particularly the Navy and you sort of had the timing was such to where if you

06:01.580 --> 06:05.260
wanted to be in the Navy you had to go to Houston on a particular time and

06:05.260 --> 06:09.300
and say hello to the draft office sort of talk about your desire to be in the

06:09.300 --> 06:17.780
Navy. Well at 18 you became draft eligible and we had to we looked at the

06:17.780 --> 06:22.140
military and some of us wanted to be in the Navy and others wanted to wait until

06:22.140 --> 06:26.980
they were drafted and I was one of those that had the desire to be in the Navy.

06:26.980 --> 06:31.060
Right so your dad took you to Houston on the day that when the draft the draft

06:31.060 --> 06:34.740
these were being put in the Navy so you timed it that way on purpose so that

06:34.740 --> 06:40.500
that's correct that's correct. Right and tell us where you were sent initially I

06:40.500 --> 06:43.700
know you were sent to the East Coast and then a long long trip to the West Coast

06:43.700 --> 06:47.860
so after you you up sort of talk about your training before you went overseas.

06:47.860 --> 06:54.420
Well there was a CB training base at Williamsburg Virginia right on the

06:54.420 --> 07:01.140
Chesapeake Bay and we were sent there for what they call boot camp still and

07:01.540 --> 07:07.820
then we were assigned to battalions and moved out to different parts of the

07:07.820 --> 07:11.460
world. Right so one and tell you went to Virginia that you realized that you

07:11.460 --> 07:15.260
were going to be assigned to the construction battalion and that you're you were

07:15.260 --> 07:20.740
going to be a CB right? Yes I was told that was a CB before yeah for we left Texas

07:20.740 --> 07:24.020
before you left Texas so you knew what you were in for and that you would be

07:24.020 --> 07:28.620
there. A three-week train ride from Virginia to California and they took quite a

07:28.620 --> 07:34.380
route. You remember that three-week train ride a lot don't you? Yes I suppose it

07:34.380 --> 07:39.500
was for security purposes but we went up into Ohio and back down to the Texas

07:39.500 --> 07:44.660
Panhandle and then the train went all the way to South Chicago and then back

07:44.660 --> 07:49.300
down to New Mexico and finally up through Salt Lake City and crossed the

07:49.300 --> 07:56.100
mountains there into California. Three weeks on the train yeah that was quite

07:56.100 --> 08:02.300
a ride and quite an indirect route to get there. Port Wainibi I believe it is in

08:02.300 --> 08:07.420
Southern California which is a base that is known for its training of

08:07.420 --> 08:12.500
CB's is one of the largest CB centers are the largest on the West Coast. Talk

08:12.500 --> 08:17.140
about that and it still exists with the museum there I believe. Well that was the

08:17.140 --> 08:24.700
base for our battalion organized itself in a big manner and went through

08:24.740 --> 08:31.180
typical training. We had all the rumors of going to Alaska or going to South

08:31.180 --> 08:40.340
Pacific at a bounded and I guess every military organization but we were being

08:40.340 --> 08:45.420
prepared. John I want you to talk about about the CB's I have always been

08:45.420 --> 08:49.140
personally just fascinated with the work that they did while some people might

08:49.140 --> 08:56.940
not consider it the big action spot of the war. It's true I mean the work

08:56.940 --> 09:00.380
could not have been fought could not have been won without what the CB's did

09:00.380 --> 09:04.780
especially in the Pacific theater and the Pacific campaign because you all

09:04.780 --> 09:08.860
built stuff. You all made something out of nothing as far as as far as a

09:08.860 --> 09:13.860
runways as far as a quatsit huts like you talk about bridges, piers and things

09:13.860 --> 09:17.700
like that. Talk about the CB's to the people that may not be familiar with

09:17.700 --> 09:23.660
exactly what the role of the CB's was in World War II. Well in an island war of

09:23.660 --> 09:32.740
course each each island had its individual problems and CB's went in and our

09:32.740 --> 09:41.500
job was to prepare air strips or to prepare buildings for training or for

09:41.500 --> 09:51.680
and some hospitals. We built our battalion built a base for PT boats in the

09:51.680 --> 09:59.780
Philippines and so we did a little bit of all kinds of construction work and that

09:59.780 --> 10:06.900
permitted those involved in the actual combat to go about their business without

10:06.900 --> 10:11.380
worrying about details maybe. Right. Well planes needed to run away to

10:11.380 --> 10:15.660
land on and once they got there they needed a place to live. Storage was a big

10:15.660 --> 10:19.940
deal obviously because there was equipment constantly being supplied to the

10:19.940 --> 10:23.780
Pacific theater where you're going to put all this stuff. One of the things you

10:23.780 --> 10:26.620
were involved in was the building of quatsit huts and not just for people to

10:26.620 --> 10:29.940
live but you talked about how they were strung together to make warehouses so

10:29.940 --> 10:35.940
you were having into construction right. Yes well I was assigned to a crew that

10:35.940 --> 10:41.540
was primarily involved in building quatsit huts. We built small ones for office

10:41.540 --> 10:48.140
recorders we built large ones for people to live in the crews and everything

10:48.140 --> 10:54.020
are we built tied them together and a way to make some very enormous warehouse

10:54.020 --> 10:59.660
facilities because the supplies that were coming to the Pacific was very

10:59.660 --> 11:05.960
enormous. When we went to the Philippines I think that there were over 150

11:05.960 --> 11:12.500
ships in Lady Gough at one time right at the time of the re invasion. Right.

11:12.500 --> 11:16.580
Right. And when we're talking about supplies we're not just talking about guns

11:16.580 --> 11:21.100
and ammo and things like that. We're talking about tanks and trucks and and the

11:21.100 --> 11:26.140
vehicles that it took to to fight the war. I mean we're talking about large

11:26.140 --> 11:31.580
large equipment that you all had to deal with in fine place for. Yes that and food.

11:31.580 --> 11:37.860
An enormous amount of food had to be brought in to serve our troops. Right. Right.

11:37.860 --> 11:42.060
And this is food I guess that you had to make sure that that didn't spoil and had

11:42.060 --> 11:46.460
to be properly cared for and all that and feed the troops. So it's just a

11:46.460 --> 11:51.780
fascinating part of the war the the Navy CBCs. When you left California initially

11:51.780 --> 11:54.780
I want to back up a little bit you first went to down south to Australia and

11:54.780 --> 11:59.140
then straight north of Australia to New Guinea before you went to the

11:59.140 --> 12:02.380
Philippines. So sort of talk about your route from California and what you did

12:02.380 --> 12:09.260
at each place. Well rather than a convoy our troop ship was alone so it went as

12:09.260 --> 12:14.860
far south as it could reasonably go and then in order to avoid Japanese

12:14.860 --> 12:20.500
submarines and then circle around and then came back north and landed on the

12:20.500 --> 12:27.580
east coast of Australia or at least we anchored for about a month before

12:27.580 --> 12:34.540
they moved us on north to New Guinea. Right. Right. And of course at that time

12:34.540 --> 12:42.460
combat was still underway on the island of New Guinea and then when they got

12:42.460 --> 12:48.700
ready to recapture the Philippine islands well then we were loaded on to

12:48.700 --> 12:55.300
transports that had all of our supplies and equipment on them and we had

12:55.300 --> 13:01.260
it north and ended up at Lady Gulf on the same day that General Mike Arthur

13:01.260 --> 13:06.180
returned. I see I see. The late take off obviously a hotspot of the of the

13:06.180 --> 13:10.060
Pacific campaign and while you say you weren't directly involved in combat

13:10.060 --> 13:13.260
operations you could you could hear it from where you were right. That's

13:13.260 --> 13:22.980
correct. They were pretty close to us anyway. Right. Right. You said that one of

13:22.980 --> 13:27.580
the things that your unit did was build piers and you believe that possibly

13:27.580 --> 13:32.480
where you were may have been involved were former president John F. Kennedy and

13:32.480 --> 13:36.220
his PT both might have docked because he was in the Philippines at one time in

13:36.220 --> 13:41.180
his in his service right. Yes there was a PT base between the island of

13:41.180 --> 13:48.140
Latia and the island of Samar. The ocean channel there was pretty narrow and

13:48.140 --> 13:54.580
PT boats should come in there and dock and resurface and make plans to go back

13:54.580 --> 14:01.820
into the ocean. Right. Right. We've got three photos that Mr. Blazons has

